Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

Hi all again. I think that, for the moment, we can leave this change opened, because we think this change is more related to following good practices (which are really good) rather than improving what we have (because we are not adding new functionalities; we are just doing the same but in a different way), and it would imply several consequences (e.g. update all the servers in which we have d-o-a-a installed to use this ansible collection).

I have created a Jira issue to review these kind of changes in which we are trying to include good practices in our components, just to define a procedure to be followed in all these possible cases. You can check it here: https://issues.redhat.com/browse/CILAB-337. In the meanwhile, as I said, I think this CR is quite good to improve the way we interact with ansible collections, but for the moment, we would prefer to wait for knowing how to really do these kind of changes.

Patch Set 4:

I guess I should have also added this to the requirements.yml for installing the ansible-galaxy requirements.

We are also missing the community.general collection in:
https://github.com/redhat-cip/dci-openshift-app-agent/blob/master/requirements.yml

From previous experience I find it's better to use an available ansible module versus using shell/command tasks.

It will do it automatically based on external dependencies of the change to be tested? 
I am saying this because the first idea that came up to my mind after checking this CR is that it would be used to record external repos included in our changes, to create a component related to that repo. Example: if I include a build-depends in my change linking to, e.g., the test-network-function repo, this will create a component for that repo with the commit used. Is it correct?

Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

I have also tested it on libvirt (hv7) with the following command, also using the Test-App-Hints and Test-Args-Hints fields in the commit message that you can see:

```
 dci-check-change 22996 <kubeconfig> -e '{ "tnf_targetpodlabels": [environment=test] }'
```

By the way, I had to include the tnf_targetpodlabels list in the CLI command and not in the commit msg because it was failing the way dci-check-change captures Test-Args-Hints for that parameter. I will propose a change to fix it in the near future. As a result of this, dci-ci-bot job will not execute the suite because tnf_targetpodlabels will be null, as it is not present in Test-Args-Hints. So it is not required to wait for dci-ci-bot result (that's why I manually run the test on libvirt with dci-check-change)

The job is here: https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/4995b172-d468-4143-8c0c-82df3dba7029/jobStates

If you check it, the test suite is executed correctly, running the access-control tests, and also, the tnf_config.yml file is configured correctly (without using prefix in our case, allowing flexibility in the way the labels are created):

```
---
targetNameSpaces:
  - name: test-check
targetPodLabels:
  - prefix: 
    name: environment
    value: test

certifiedcontainerinfo:

certifiedoperatorinfo:

...
``` 

Regarding Charles' comment, I have included the changes in Mavenir repo in this PR, to be merged when this change is merged: https://github.com/dci-labs/mavenir-tnf-config/pull/2

And as I commented before, it has been tested successfully in dallas too, so the change is ready for review and to be merged if you find it fine

Well, not at all. The thing is, I had a lot of problems by defining a list variable in Test-Args-Hints argument in the commit, so what I did is to pass the tnf_targetpodlabels list when running dci-check-change in hv2 CLI, and there it is working fine. The default libvirt test will not execute the CNF Cert Suite in fact because that parameter is not defined by default in Test-Args-Hints, and that's the workaround I did to test it on hv2. But even not defining the labels, the job will pass on libvirt.

In fact, this is a feature that I want to include in a future change for dci-check-change: to parse correctly complex variables like lists.

Apart from this, the change is working fine, at least for dallas-pipelines PR154 (the last failures mainly come from dallas-pipelines PR138, which is example-cnf update, and I need to review it before merging that PR). And also, there were some jobs failing some hours ago but it was due to a different issue, fixed in CR 23062, or problems with the CNF Cert Suite but not related to d-o-a-a that are under review by CNF Cert Suite tem.

So, as I said, this change is ready to be merged.
